<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    X.400 implementation issues
From:       <a href="?a=95837784200015&r=1&w=2">Carlos Fernandez</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198612">1986-12-16 13:07:50</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026834&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026834&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Virginia Tech's Communication Network Services is developing an X.400-based
networking scheme whose objective is the interconnection of the many
different types of computer equipment.  Several issues have arisen for
which we do not have satisfactory answers or information in hand that
would help in analyzing the problem.  Help in any of these matters
would be greatly appreciated:

o What is the current level of support expected of different information
  types?  We are specifically concerned about remote UAEs in workstations.
  The initial implementation will only support text and ForwardedIPMessage
  types.  What work is being done in other types?  Where can we find
  documentation on IA5 and ITA types?

o Are there any implementations of P3 in existence?  We are considering the
  option of providing MHS services to PCs or workstations that are connected
  asynchronously, without an ethernet-type of connection.  Given the
  constraint on the number of physical ports in the MTA server,
  we cannot have a permanent transport connection between a given PC and
  the MTA server.  Consequently, we may need to modify P3 and disallow
  operations originated by the MTA.

Please send your comments/replies/questions directly to
fernandc%vtvm1.bitnet@wiscvm.

Carlos Fernandez                         Bitnet: FERNANDC@VTVM1
Communications Network Services
Plaza 1 B3, Virginia Tech
Blacksburg, VA 24061
